        <example>
          <statement>
            <p>
                Find the value of uknown angles marked in letters in the figure below.
            </p>
          

            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="polygon">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{quotes,angles}
                    
                    \draw[thick,blue] (-4,3)--(2,3);
                    \draw[thick,blue] (1,3)--(4,0);
                    \draw[thick,blue] (3,1)--(1,-3);
                    \draw[thick,blue] (4,-3)--(-4,-3);
                    \draw[thick,blue] (-3,3)--(-3,-3);

                    \draw[thick,blue] (-3,3) coordinate(a)--(1,3) coordinate(b)--(3,1)coordinate(c)
                    pic["$x$", draw=green, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=0.5cm]
                    {angle=a--b--c};

                    \draw[thick,blue] (1,-3) coordinate(g)--(3,1) coordinate(f)--(4,0)coordinate(d)
                    pic["$y$", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=0.5cm]
                    {angle=g--f--d};

                    \draw[thick,blue] (4,-3) coordinate(h)--(1,-3) coordinate(g)--(3,1)coordinate(f)
                    pic["$60^\circ$", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=0.5cm]
                    {angle=h--g--f};

                    \draw[thick,blue] (3,1) coordinate(f)--(1,3) coordinate(c)--(2,3)coordinate(b)
                    pic["$50^\circ$", draw=red, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=0.8cm]
                    {angle=f--c--b};

                    \draw[thick,red] (-2.5,-3) coordinate(k)--(-2.5,-2.5) coordinate(j)--(-3,-2.5)coordinate(c);
                    \draw[thick,red] (-2.5,3) coordinate(p)--(-2.5,2.5) coordinate(q)--(-3,2.5)coordinate(r);              
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>50^\circ, 60^\circ</m> and <m>y</m> are exterior angles. 
                There sum of interior angle and its corresponding exterior angle is <m>180^\circ.</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
              Therefore: <me>50^\circ + x = 180^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>x = 180^\circ - 50^\circ</me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x = 130^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                The corresponding interior angle for angle <m>60^\circ</m> is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    180^\circ - 60^\circ = 120^\circ
                </me>    
            </p>
            <p>
                To find the corresponding interior angle for <m>y,</m> in the pentagon, you know that interior angles in a pentagon add up to <m>540^\circ.</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore: 
                <me>
                    90^\circ + 90^\circ + 120^\circ + 130^\circ + (\text{ corresponding interior angle for }y) = 540^\circ.
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    430^\circ + \text{ corresponding interior angle for }y = 540^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \text{ corresponding interior angle for } y = 540^\circ - 430^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \text{ corresponding interior angle for } y = 110^\circ 
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                Since we have found the corresponding interior angle for <m>y,</m> to find the exterior angle <m>y,</m> we take;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    y = 180^\circ - \text{ corresponding interior angle for } y 
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    y = 180^\circ - 110^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    y = 70^\circ
                </me>
                
            </p>
            
        </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the number of sides(n) of a regular polygon when all the interior angles of the polygon are <m>135^\circ</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <term>Method 1</term>
                </p>
                <p>
                    We can find the number if sides of a polygon from the given formula:
                    <me>
                        \text{Exterior angle of the polygon }= \frac{360^\circ}{n}
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p> First find the exterior angle of the polygon as shown:
                    <me>
                        \text{Exterior angle of the polygon } = 180^\circ - \text{interior angle of the polygon}
                    </me> 
                </p>
                <p> Therefore:
                    <me>
                        \text{Exterior angle of the polygon } = 180^\circ - 140^\circ 
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        \text{Exterior angle of the polygon } = 40^\circ
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Thus, using this formula:
                    <me>
                        \text{Exterior angle of the polygon }= \frac{360^\circ}{n}
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        40^\circ = \frac{360^\circ}{n}
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        n = \frac{360^\circ}{40^\circ}
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore; <m>n = 9 </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <term>Method 2</term>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Alternatively, we can find the number of sides of the polygon as shown below:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        \text{ Sum of interior angles = Size of interior angle } \times \text{n}
                    </me>
                   
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        \text{ Sum of interior angles } = 140^\circ \times{n} = 140n
                        
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    Also, sum of interior angles can be given by multiplying <m>180^\circ</m> by the number of trialgles <m>(n - 2)</m> in the polygon.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        180^\circ(n-2)
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore:
                    <me>
                      180^\circ(n-2) = 140n
                    </me>
                    <me>
                      180n - 360 = 140n
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    Collecting like terms, we get:
                    <me>
                        180n - 140n = 360
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        40n = 360
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        n = \frac{360}{40}
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    <me>
                        n = 9
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
                
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        
